Organization = {{S Asia Inst Sci \& Engn}},
Abstract = {{The exponential growth of electronic form of textual documents in both
   public and proprietary storage force researchers to find way to
   efficiently extract meaningful, actionable information from these
   documents. Document clustering has find its niche in this area. This
   paper proposes a document representational model based on distributional
   semantics, the law of distributional semantics says that the linguist
   terms that appear with similar distribution in a language corpus
   generally have similar meaning. This representation of document model
   uses only those terms (linguistic feature) that have same distribution
   over a given collection of documents. So to find this, it is needed to
   find out the distributional terms by using distributional criteria and
   then representing the documents by only these distributional terms. A
   novel similarity measure is proposed over these documents that also
   utilized the very nature of distributional semantics in similarity
   calculation. Finally, hierarchal agglomerative clustering (HAC) is used
   to produce the final clusters. Standard text mining datasets are used to
   measure the effectiveness of this approach. The evaluation is based on
   purity of clusters and proposed approach achieved far better clustering
