Month = {{OCT}},
Abstract = {{Document clustering is important for a variety of information needs and
   applications such as collection management, summary and analysis.
   Especially, mining biomedical texts for knowledge discovery and
   hypothesis generation has become a very active field due to the immense
   availability of large biomedical textual database. However, most of the
   previous techniques on clustering biomedical documents have not used the
   rich information in the MeSH and Thesaurus. Furthermore, they only
   considered the keywords for document clustering without taking into
   consideration of concepts. In the proposed work, we develop a clustering
   algorithm using the semantic similarity measure that makes use of
   MeSH/WordNet ontology and the concept extracted. Initially, the
   biomedical documents are extracted from the Pub Med and the
   preprocessing techniques such as, stop word removal and stemming will be
   performed. Then, the concept is extracted using the mutual information
   defined in the information retrieval system and for every concept; the
   parent and child neighbors are identified from the MeSH/WordNet
   ontology. Then, the document clustering algorithm is devised using the
   semantic similarity measure that makes use of the weights of concept and
   its parent and child neighbors from MeSH/WordNet. Finally, the
   experimentation is carried out using the PubMed documents and the
   performance of the proposed technique is compared against the term-based
   technique using evaluation metrics. The accuracy obtained is 48.5 for
   Word Net ontology and 49.5 for MeSH ontology.}},
