Abstract = {{Information retrieval (IR) systems are designed, in general, to satisfy
   the information need of a user who expresses it by means of a query, by
   providing him with a subset of documents selected from a collection and
   ordered by decreasing relevance to the query. Such systems are based on
   IR models, which define how to represent the documents and the query, as
   well as how to determine the relevance of a document for a query. In
   this article, we present a new IR model based on concepts taken from
   both IR and digital signal processing (like Fourier analysis of signals
   and filtering). This allows the whole IR process to be seen as a
   physical phenomenon, where the query corresponds to a signal, the
   documents correspond to filters, and the determination of the relevant
   documents to the query is done by filtering that signal. Tests showed
   that the quality of the results provided by this IR model is comparable
   with the state-of-the-art.}},
