   additional information about users besides their queries. In the past
   two decades or so, PIR has received extensive attention in both academia
   and industry. This article surveys the literature of personalization in
   text retrieval, following a framework for aspects or factors that can be
   used for personalization. The framework consists of additional
   information about users that can be explicitly obtained by asking users
   for their preferences, or implicitly inferred from users' search
   behaviors. Users' characteristics and contextual factors such as tasks,
   time, location, etc., can be helpful for personalization. This article
