Abstract = {{This paper formulates a novel approach to spoken document information
   retrieval for instinctive speech corpora. The conventional method for
   this problem is to make use of an Automatic Speech Recognizer (ASR)
   integrated with the typical information retrieval method. However, ASRs
   tend to produce transcripts of spontaneous speech with momentous word
   error rate, which is a negative aspect of standard retrieval system. To
   prevail over such a constraint, we propose a method for spoken document
   retrieval based on spoken keyword spotting using Auto Associative Neural
   Networks (AANN). The proposed work concerns the exploit of the
   distribution capturing capability of an auto associative neural network
   for spoken keyword detection. It involves sliding a frame-based keyword
   template along the audio documents and by means of confidence score
   acquired from the normalized squared error of AANN to competently search
   for a match. This work provides a new spoken keyword spotting algorithm
   based spoken documents clustering. The experimental results recommend
   that the proposed method is promising for retrieving relevant documents
