   Nuance; Grammarly; VoiceBox Technologies; Yandex; Textkernel; Zalando SE}},
Abstract = {{Most current chatbot engines are designed to reply to user utterances
   based on existing utterance-response (or Q-R)1 pairs. In this paper, we
   present DocChat, a novel information retrieval approach for chatbot
   engines that can leverage unstructured documents, instead of Q-R pairs,
   to respond to utterances. A learning to rank model with features
   designed at different levels of granularity is proposed to measure the
   relevance between utterances and responses directly. We evaluate our
   proposed approach in both English and Chinese: (i) For English, we
   evaluate DocChat on WikiQA and QASent, two answer sentence selection
   tasks, and compare it with state-of-the-art methods. Reasonable
   improvements and good adaptability are observed. (ii) For Chinese, we
   compare DocChat with Xiaolce(2), a famous chitchat engine in China, and
   side-by-side evaluation shows that DocChat is a perfect complement for
   chatbot engines using Q-R pairs as main source of responses.}},
