Abstract = {{Significant amounts of information available today contain references to
   places on earth. Traditionally such information has been held as
   structured data and was the concern of Geographic Information Systems
   (GIS). However, increasing amounts of data in the form of unstructured
   text are available for indexing and retrieval that also contain spatial
   references. This monograph describes the field of Geographic Information
   Retrieval (GIR) that seeks to develop spatially-aware search systems and
   support user's geographical information needs. Important concepts with
   respect to storing, querying and analysing geographical information in
   computers are introduced, before user needs and interaction in the
   context of GIR are explored. The task of associating documents with
   coordinates, prior to their indexing and ranking forms the core of any
   GIR system, and different approaches and their implications are
   discussed. Evaluating the resulting systems and their components, and
   different paradigms for doing so continue to be an important area of
   research in GIR and are illustrated through a number of examples. The
