   rely on the Web to seek for health information for self-diagnosis.
   However, research has shown that current search engines are failing to
   deliver effective search results due to the inability of laypeople to
   formulate good queries because of lack of domain knowledge and
   unfamiliarity with the medical vocabulary and concepts. This article
   attempts to address this by proposing a Selective Collection Enrichment
   approach that uses three different external resources to enrich a user
   query, thus generating three different expanded queries. In addition, we
   deploy pre-retrieval query performance predictors to select an expanded
   query that is most likely to perform better when retrieving on a local
   collection being searched. Furthermore, we evaluate the effects of
   combining several pre-retrieval query performance predictors' scores
   using data fusion techniques for Selective Collection Enrichment. Our
   empirical evaluation shows marked improvement in the retrieval
   performance in terms of nDCG@10 when the Selective Collection Enrichment
